					<p>Za <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-657" type="subject">Dokumentační</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-657" type="subject">akci</term> přijal: <date when="1945-11-19">19. 11. 1945</date></p>
					<p><persName ref="#ehri_dc_shek_zeev">Scheck</persName></p>
					<p>Za archiv: <persName ref="#ehri_dc_schmiedt_alexander">Alex. Schmiedt</persName></p>
				</div>
				<div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
					<pb facs="EHRI-DC-006_01.jpg" n="1"/>
					<p>Statement</p>
					<p>Written with Mr. <persName ref="#ehri_dc_klinger_ota">Ota Klinger</persName>, born <date when="1910-07-17">17. 7. 1910</date>, residing in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName> I., <placeName
							ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Betlémská</placeName> ul. 8., former <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoner</term> in the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449"
							type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName>, <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0" type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName>, and <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-851" type="camp">Schwarzheide</placeName><term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">concentration camps</term>, <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3077311/czechia.html">Czech</placeName> nationality, profession clerk.</p>
					<p>On <date when="1941-11-30">November 30th, 1941</date>, I departed on the <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3067696/prague.html">Prague</placeName>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">AK II transport </term> to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_ghettos-449" type="ghetto">Theresienstadt</placeName>, where I remained until <date when="1943-12"
							>December, 1943</date>, when I was sent via <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> to <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0" type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName>. When we arrived in
							<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-0" type="camp">Auschwitz</placeName> at night, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoners</term>, assisted by <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SSmen</term>, led us from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">freight trains</term>. On the way, they warned us that everything we took with us
						would be taken away and that we would likely meet the same fate as the millions who had perished in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-499" type="subject">gas chambers</term>. Due to the large numbers of arriving <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transports</term>, we lived with this thought for 2 days in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">sauna</term>, where the most terrible <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">suffering</term> and misery occured. Piles of frozen <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-515" type="subject">corpses</term>, bleeding people who were <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">shot</term> while leaving the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">wooden buildings</term>. On the way from the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-522" type="subject">train</term> and here as well we <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">suffered</term> from an indescribable <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">thirst</term>. In desperation, we collected anything we could to squeeze out any drops to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">drink</term>. In
						exchange for gold, diamonds, or money, we got a cup of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">tea</term>. In the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">family</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">camp</term>, in which we were later placed, we found many of our friends, but we barely recognized them because they were so <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-569" type="subject">malnourished</term>. That was the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> that arrived on <date when="1943-09-06">September 6th,
							1943</date>. We were with them until <date when="1944-03-07">March 7th, 1944</date>, when the whole <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-521" type="subject">transport</term> was sent to the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-534" type="subject">gas chamber</term>, although they were told that they would be sent to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">labor</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">camp</term> in <placeName ref="http://www.geonames.org/3096372/kedzierzyn-kozle.html">Heidebreck</placeName>.</p>
					<p>At the time, I <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-944" type="subject">potato kitchen</term>, where I was continuously <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">terrorized</term> by its <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-484" type="subject">leader</term> (a <placeName ref="https://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html"
							>Pole</placeName> named <persName ref="#ehri_dc_lada_vaclav">Vacek</persName>) (<persName ref="#ehri_dc_lada_vaclav">Václav Lada</persName>) and by the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SSmen</term> overseeing the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">kitchen</term>. We <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">worked</term> from 4 in the morning to 6, or sometimes 8, in the evening without stopping,
						except for when we could <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">eat</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">lunch</term>. If <persName ref="#ehri_dc_lada_vaclav">Vacek</persName> thought we were <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-556" type="subject">working</term> too
						slowly, he would take a cane and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beat</term> all of us. Although he himself <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-660" type="subject">stole</term> whole bags of <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term> and took from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">kitchen</term> kilos of <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">sugar</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">margarine</term> that were designated as meager <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-834" type="subject">rations</term> for the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoners</term> and <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-189"
							type="subject">exchanged</term> them for tobacco and jewels, allowing him to live a debauched life, all it took for him to satisfy his <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">sadistic</term> whims in the cruelest ways was for him
						to find in the pockets of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1057" type="subject">potato peelers</term>, or in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> left aside for the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1057" type="subject">peeler</term>’s <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-819" type="subject">family</term><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-822" type="subject"
							>members</term>, a single <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potato</term>. Then he would order the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoner</term> to put the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potato</term> in his mouth, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-709" type="subject">squat</term> on a stool, pick up another stool in his hands, and <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-709" type="subject">exercise</term>. When the poor man could no longer continue, <persName ref="#ehri_dc_lada_vaclav">Vacek</persName> would use a cane or he would break off the metal part of a shovel and <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">hit</term> him with the shaft. If the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoner</term> was still able to move, he would make him spin around the
						shovel until he got <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">dizzy</term>. Then he would pour <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">water</term> all over him and kick the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">tortured</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">to the brink of death</term>, collapsed man, throw him into a tub full of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">ice cold</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">water</term> that was used to wash <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potatoes</term> in <date>January</date> when it was <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">freezing</term> cold. Then, he kicked him out of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-944" type="subject">potato kitchen</term> and let him return to the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">freezing</term> cold weather. Even the strongest and <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-791" type="subject">healthiest</term> succumbed to <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">pneumonia</term>.</p>
					<p>For one <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">soup</term> we would volunteer in the evenings to clean up after 100 <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">potato</term> and <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">turnip</term><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1057" type="subject">peelers</term>. Everything was worked out to <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">torture</term> us. We would cast countless hectoliters of <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">water</term> onto the floor and if the <placeName
							ref="https://www.geonames.org/798544/republic-of-poland.html">Pole</placeName> or the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SS</term> would find a single <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832"
							type="subject">potato</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">peel</term> they would order us to play sports. To the delight of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1216" type="subject">SSmen</term>, they would get the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">kitchen</term><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoners</term> to play the game with us. With a several kilo (5-7) heavy wooden object, they
						ordered the condemned to run around a cauldron. They had to perform certain drills, such as squats, nieder-auf, to the ground and back up. They made them exercise in front of the open fire in the cauldrons. If the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoner</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">fainted</term>, they poured <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">water</term> on him and he would have to continue exercising while being severely
							<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beaten</term>. Many people <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-745" type="subject">didn’t live</term> much longer after this game.</p>
					<pb facs="EHRI-DC-006_02.jpg" n="2"/>
					<p>The so-called <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-834" type="subject">Fassung</term> was also interesting. We would commute from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">B II</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">family</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/terezin-terms-keyword-jmp-594" type="subject">camp</term> to the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-507" type="subject">Männerlager</term>, where they handed out enough <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">foodstuffs</term> for a week for 10,000 people from the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term> to us. We traveled back <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-939" type="subject">yoked</term> like <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-939" type="subject">horses</term>, generally at a trot. This is how we had to load bags of <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">flour</term> and other <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">foodstuffs</term> while we were continually whipped with canes. We had to load 35 cents of
							<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-832" type="subject">flour</term> onto the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-939" type="subject">cart</term> in 5 minutes, which was unbelievably difficult for us, and then pull the
							<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-939" type="subject">cart</term> all the way to the neighboring <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-496" type="subject">camp</term>. The <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-562" type="subject">beatings</term> were so cruel that <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">prisoners</term> would collapse under the <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-939" type="subject">cart</term> and be run over by the heavily laden vehicle. They would end up with <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">fractures</term>, <term
							ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">internal</term>
						<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-292" type="subject">bleeding</term>, etc.</p>
					<p>Signature:</p>
					<p><persName ref="#ehri_dc_klinger_ota">Klinger Ota</persName></p>
